knowledge_graph.title: Raccoon
knowledge_graph.description: The raccoon, also spelled racoon and sometimes called the common raccoon or northern raccoon to distinguish it from the other species, is a mammal native to North America. It is the largest of the procyonid family, having a body length of 40 to 70 cm, and a body weight of 5 to 26 kg.

related_questions.question: Are raccoons a danger to humans?
related_questions.snippet: Raccoons are most dangerous to humans when they feel threatened or trapped or need to protect their young. Before attacking, raccoons may bluff or try to intimidate you. They might bear their teeth and claws, vocalize aggressively or even charge at you.
related_questions.title: Are Raccoons Dangerous? - Urban Jungle Wildlife Removal

related_questions.question: What to do if you see a raccoon?
related_questions.snippet: Never try to catch or directly handle a raccoon. Stay calm. A panicked raccoon may run further inside your house and may cause damage. Contain pets in rooms away from the raccoon and close doors to other parts of the house. Open doors and windows near the raccoon that lead outside.
related_questions.title: What to do about raccoons | The Humane Society of the United States

related_questions.question: Where do raccoons go during the day?
related_questions.snippet: Raccoons are adaptable animals that live in both urban and wild environments. During the day, they retreat to their dens or other sheltered areas but may come out to forage for food or bask in the sun.
related_questions.title: dens

related_questions.question: Why is a raccoon in my yard?
related_questions.snippet: The main draw for raccoons coming into your yard is a yummy looking snack. Of course, to a raccoon, this can be very different from what we humans might think of as appetizing. Raccoons will feast on everything from fruits and nuts, to worms and insects, to garbage in your trash cans.
